#from stackoverflow
def calculate_pvalues(df):
    dfcols = pd.DataFrame(columns=df.columns)
    pvalues = dfcols.transpose().join(dfcols, how='outer')
    for r in df.columns:
        for c in df.columns:
            tmp = df[df[r].notnull() & df[c].notnull()]
            pvalues[r][c] = round(stats.pearsonr(tmp[r], tmp[c])[1], 4)
    return pvalues

But if we view the plot (y:median_sale_price and y:stars) it shows that higher stars get businesses with less nedian_sale_price That can indicate that the second part of the hypothesis might not be correct (H: Expensive areas have more and better businesses)
